## 4. Docking Detection Algorithm

Inside `tick()`, after the existing target detection block (line 188 in current code), add the docking detection logic:

```js
// ── Docking detection (after targetIndexRef is set) ─────────
const dockState = dockingStateRef.current;

if (dockState === 'none' && bestIdx >= 0) {
    const dockStar = stars[bestIdx];
    const dockViewZ = dockStar.viewZ;

    // Check if star is centered enough for docking
    const projX_d = cx + (dockStar._rotX1 / dockViewZ) * focalLength;
    const projY_d = cy - (dockStar._rotY2 / dockViewZ) * focalLength;
    const centerDist = Math.sqrt(
        (projX_d - cx) ** 2 + (projY_d - cy) ** 2
    );

    // Magnetic pull zone (outer ring)
    if (dockViewZ < MAGNET_THRESHOLD_Z && dockViewZ > DOCKING_THRESHOLD_Z) {
        dockingStateRef.current = 'magnet';
        dockingTargetIdxRef.current = bestIdx;
    }

    // Docking trigger (inner zone)
    if (dockViewZ < DOCKING_THRESHOLD_Z && centerDist < DOCKING_CENTER_MAX) {
        dockingStateRef.current = 'approaching';
        dockingTargetIdxRef.current = bestIdx;
        dockingStartTimeRef.current = performance.now();
        dockingProgressRef.current = 0;
        dockingStarScaleRef.current = 1;
        inputFrozenRef.current = true;
    }
}
```

The detection is conservative: the star must be both close (viewZ < 18) AND near screen center (< 50px). This prevents accidental docking when stars pass peripherally.

